Arrian, 6.27.1<!--</A>ARRIAN6-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
This was in Carmania. Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/9*.html#10.22
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(9.10.22‑28)
	</A>
gives a lurid account of this celebration; so also Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#67
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Alexander</I>, 67.1‑3</A>. Arrian
(6.28.1‑2)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN6-->
states that this story was not told by Ptolemy or Aristobulus, and that he himself did not believe it. It may be connected, however, with the tradition of dramatic and athletic games held at this time in celebration of the safe return of both army and fleet (E. Badian, <I>Classical Quarterly</I>, 52 (1958), 152<!--</A>JOURNAL:CQ:52, copyright until at least 2028-->). But both Philip
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/16D*.html#87
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Book 16.87.1)
	</A>
and Alexander
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#72.5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 72.5)
	</A>
were fond of the comus in general. See Addenda<!-- zzz -->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
For Alexander's disciplinary measures at this time cp. 	<A HREF="
