<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
The Harpalus story was well known (Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/5.html#41.4
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Alexander</I>, 41.4</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Phocion*.html#21
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Phocion</I>, 21‑22</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte13.html#5
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 13.5.9</A>), but was told


<A ID="p435x"></A>here, in addition to Diodorus, only by Curtius. In the loss of parts of that text, only the end of the story remains
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#2
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(10.2.1‑3)</A>, told in a similar way to that here. The account of these events in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Demosthenes*.html#25
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Demosthenes</I>, 25‑26</A>, may plausibly be ascribed to Theopompus, at least in part.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
Harpalus was not actually a satrap, but director general of the royal treasury.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
She is mentioned by Athenaeus, 13, 586<SPAN CLASS="small">C</SPAN><!--</A>ATHENAEUS586-->, who refers to accounts of her by Theopompus and Cleitarchus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
Athenaeus, 13, 586<SPAN CLASS="small">C</SPAN><!--</A>ATHENAEUS586-->. The considerable evidence on these two is collected by Berve, <I>Alexanderreich</I>, 2, nos. 231 and 676.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#2.1
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 10.2.1‑3</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#19.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 18.19.2</A>. The collaboration of Antipater and Olympias is odd, for they were ordinarily hostile to each other.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte13.html#5
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 13.5.9</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#2.4
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 10.2.4‑7</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte13.html#5
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 13.5.2‑5</A>. Diodorus refers to this later with greater detail as one of the causes of the Lamian War
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#8.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Book 18.8.2‑7)</A>. The time was midsummer of 324 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
This story appears in differing versions. Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#2.9
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(10.2.9‑11)
	</A>
tells only of the payment of the debts, without specifying either the number or the identity of the beneficiaries; 10,000 talents were made available, and 130 were left over. Justin
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#11
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(12.11.2‑3)
	</A>
says that 20,000 talents were distributed,


<A ID="p439x"></A>an act equally welcome to debtors and creditors. Plutarch
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#70.2
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Alexander</I>, 70.2)
	</A>
uses the same total as Curtius (9870), but says that these were the debts of the guests at the mass marriage in Susa. Curtius expresses astonishment that the soldiers were so in debt. (From whom, as a matter of fact, would ten thousand soldiers borrow a talent each?) At all events, Arrian
(7.12.1)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
states specifically that the soldiers were Macedonian and each received a gift of a talent.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
The mutiny at Opis, continued from
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#108.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 108.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#2.30
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 10.2.30</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#11
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.11.8</A>. Arrian
(7.8.3)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
says that he merely pointed out the ringleaders.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
Anticles was archon at Athens from July 325 to June 324 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> L. Cornelius Lentulus and Q. Publilius Philo were consuls in 327 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> (Broughton, 1.145). In his narrative, Diodorus has reached, actually, the late summer of 324 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<A ID="p441x"></A>The narrative of Curtius is lost down to the story of Alexander's death.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
Arrian
(7.6.3)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
states that these thousand formed a fifth squadron of the Companion Cavalry.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
Peucestes had been rewarded with the satrapy of Persia after saving Alexander's life
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17E*.html#99.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 99.4)</A>. Of all Alexander's generals he showed the greatest willingness to conciliate the Persians. Arrian has described these new units earlier
(7.11.3‑4)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
but places this event a year later
(7.23.1)<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#71.5
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 71.5</A>;
Arrian, 7.12
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
(stating that these were the children of the veterans who returned to Macedonia);
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#4
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.4.6
	</A>
(under 300 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
Diodorus's topography is confused. His tradition (shared by Curtius) does not place the mutiny at Opis, as does Arrian; hence Alexander is still at Susa. The "Carian" villages were in Babylonia
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/19B*.html#12
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Book 19.12.1)
	</A>
and so on the right bank of the Tigris; Sittacenê was on the left bank
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#65.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 65.2)</A>. The location of Sambana is unknown. Perhaps Alexander


<A ID="p443x"></A>crossed the Tigris twice. By "Tigris" in the text is not meant the Pasitigris
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 67.1)</A>, which was south-east of Susa; the city was on the Choaspes and Eulaeus Rivers
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/15C*.html#3.4
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo, 15.3.4 <SPAN CLASS="small">[728]</SPAN>)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
These are probably the Eretrians whom Herodotus mentions
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/6C*.html#119
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(6.119)
	</A>
as having been carried off by Xerxes, although he places them nearer to Susa. The place is mentioned again,
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/19B*.html#19.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 19.19.2</A>. In their tenacious Hellenism, they anticipated the settlers of the Hellenistic period (cp. F. Grosso, <I>Rivista di Filologia Classica</I>, 36 (1958), 350‑375).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note50" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref50
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">50</A>
The age-old road from Baghdad to Hamadan, the main route from Mesopotamia to Iran.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note51" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref51
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">51</A>
This was Nysa. Arrian
(7.13.1)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
gives slightly different figures: formerly 150,000 mares, now 50,000.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note52" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref52
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">52</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#12
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.12.11</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#72
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 72</A>;
Arrian, 7.14<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note53" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">53</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte13.html#5
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 13.5.1‑8</A>. The war did not actually break out until after Alexander's death, and Diodorus gives an account of it later
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Book 18.8 ff.)
	</A>
which repeats some of this material.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note54" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">54</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#106.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 106.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note55" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">55</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#72.3
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 72.3</A>;
Arrian, 7.15.1‑3<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->. This activity took place in the winter of 324/3 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> and was intended to solace Alexander's grief for the death of Hephaestion.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note56" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
