The name is not otherwise reported.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#73
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 73.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
Arrian does not think that Alexander heeded the warnings of the Chaldaeans, but quotes Aristobulus
(7.17.5‑6)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
to the effect that Alexander did wish to avoid the city, but could not pass it because of the swamps.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#13
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.13.5</A>. This was the celebrated philosopher of Abdera, of the school of Democritus. He had been with Alexander throughout the campaign.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A>
That is, astrology. It is odd that Diodorus should speak so well of Greek rationalism, when in this case the Chaldaeans knew better.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#64.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 64.4</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note64" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">64</A>
Hegesias (as the name appears in the Attic inscriptions) was archon from July 324 to June 323 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> The consuls of 326 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> were C. Poetelius Libo Visolus and L. Papirius Cursor (Broughton, 1.146). The Olympic Games were held in the summer of 324 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#109
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 109.1)</A>. The name of the victor is given as Macinnas by Eusebius. The time was actually the spring of 323 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note65" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref65
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">65</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#13
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.13.1‑2</A>;
Arrian, 7.15.4‑6
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
(embassies from the west);
19.1‑2
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
(embassies from the Greeks). Arrian
(7.15.5‑6)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
expresses doubt about the embassy from Rome, reported among others by Cleitarchus (Jacoby, <I>Fragmente der Griechische Historiker</I>, no. 137, F 31; from
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/3*.html#57
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pliny, <I>Naturalis Historia</I>, 3.57</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note66" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref66
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">66</A>
These ingenious and methodical arrangements of Alexander's court are not otherwise reported.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note67" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">67</A>
That is, Craterus loved Alexander as the king, Hephaestion loved Alexander for himself. On the relations between Craterus and Hephaestion cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#47.5
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 47.5‑57</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note68" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref68
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">68</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17B*.html#37.5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 37.5‑6</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note69" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">69</A>
Hephaestion's usage here suggests the <I>pluralis majestatis</I>. He can hardly mean anyone but himself.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note70" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref70
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">70</A>
A similar account of Hephaestion's funeral was probably given by Curtius and is now lost from the manuscript book 10. The references in Justin
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#12
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(12.12.12)</A>, Plutarch
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#72
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Alexander</I>, 72)</A>, and Arrian
(7.14)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
are briefer, and located it before, not after, the Cossaean campaign. See Addenda<!-- zzz -->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note71" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref71
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">71</A>
These were probably medallions or small images to be worn in wreaths, as one wore images of the gods. It was a common ancient practice, employed later in the case of the Hellenistic kings and the Roman emperors.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note72" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">72</A>
The brevity of Diodorus's account leaves the meaning a little obscure. It is possible that the ground plan was divided into thirty transverse compartments, each thus about 22 feet wide and 220 yards long. Each of these could be roofed with flat timbers to support the next higher section of the pyre.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note73" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref73
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">73</A>
Justin
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#12
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(12.12.12)
	</A>
gives the same figure; Plutarch
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#72.3
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Alexander</I>, 72.3)
	</A>
and Arrian
(7.14.8)<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->, 10,000 talents.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note74" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">74</A>
Lucian (<I>Calumniae non temere credendum</I>, 17)<!--</A>LUCIAN--> gives a fuller account of Hephaestion's deification; he received


<A ID="p461x"></A>temples and precincts in the cities, his name was used in the most solemn of oaths, and he received sacrifice as a <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">πάρεδρος καὶ ἀλεξίκακος θεός</SPAN>. No archaeological record of any of this remains (C. Habicht, <I>Gottesmenschentum und griechische Städte</I>, 1956), and the ancient tradition was various. Justin
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#12
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(12.12.12)
	</A>
reports, like Diodorus, that Alexander ordered that Hephaestion was to be worshipped "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ut deum</SPAN>." Plutarch
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#72.2
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Alexander</I>, 72.2)
	</A>
states that Ammon recommended that he should be honoured as a hero, and so did he also according to Arrian
(7.23.6)<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->, after first refusing to allow him divine worship
(7.14.7)<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->. The term <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">πάρεδρος</SPAN> is odd: elsewhere it seems to mean a priest (G. E. Bean, <I>Journal of Hellenic Studies</I>, 72 (1952), 118<!--</A>JOURNAL:JHS, copyright until at least 2022-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note75" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">75</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#73.3
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 73.3‑4</A>, says that the prisoner had been miraculously freed by Serapis;
Arrian, 7.24.1‑3<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->, that he had not been held in bonds.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note76" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">76</A>
The significance of the royal throne in the Orient has appeared in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#note17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 66.3‑7 (p306, note 17)</A><!-- Loeb has "note 2" which I adjusted -->. If the man was a native, he may have regarded it as a sanctuary, or at least as a place of refuge from the pursuing guards; in Arrian's account, they did not venture to remove him by force "because of some Persian custom." (According to the anecdote traced back to Trogus by O. Sell (Pompeius Trogus, <I>Fragmenta</I>,


<A ID="p463x"></A>1956, 109 f.), it was "capital" for anyone to sit on the throne of king of Persia.) Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#73.4
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Alexander</I>, 73.4</A>, states that he was a Greek. It is possible that he did not put on the royal garments, but merely held them. Later references to the significance of the throne are Dio,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/50*.html#10.2
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
50.10.2</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/56*.html#29
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
56.29.1</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Historia_Augusta/Septimius_Severus*.html#1.9
	"TARGET="Historia_Augusta_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Script. Hist. Aug., <I>Septimius Severus</I>, 1.9</A>. See Addenda<!-- zzz -->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A>
Either because he was too frightened to speak, or because he did not speak Greek. Plutarch makes him claim to have been inspired by Serapis, but this did not save him from execution.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#74
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 74.1</A>. Arrian
(7.24.3)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
reports only that he was tortured to make him explain his actions.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A>
Or, perhaps, "about his death"; cp. note 1 above.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
The "Note 1" mentioned is a critical note to the Greek text, at <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τελευτῆς</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">σημεῖον αὐτῷ περὶ τῆς τελευτῆς</SPAN>), which reads:
		<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Possibly for <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τελευτῆς</SPAN>, as Fischer, or <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τοῦ βασιλέως τελευτῆς</SPAN>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note80" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref80
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">80</A>
Arrian
(7.22)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
tells this story earlier than the one about the throne, and gives various accounts about the incident of


<A ID="p465x"></A>lost diadem and its recovery; it was the other boats which became lost, but Alexander sent a pilot and rescued them.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note81" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref81
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">81</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#13
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.13.7</A>. These events are described from the royal journal more circumstantially by Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#75.3
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Alexander</I>, 75.3</A>, and
Arrian, 7.24.4‑25.1<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->. Medius belonged to a noble family of Larisa and had accompanied Alexander as a personal friend, not in a military capacity (Berve, <I>Alexanderreich</I>, 2, no. 521). Aelian
	<A HREF="
https://penelope.uchicago.edu/aelian/varhist3.html#chap23
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Varia Historia</I>, 3.23)</A> gives a day-by‑day account of Alexander's drinking and resting during the last three weeks of his life, crediting this to Eumenes of Cardia, the keeper of the journal, but gives the month wrongly as Dius. See Addenda<!-- zzz -->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note82" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref82
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">82</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#13
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.13.8‑9</A>. Arrian
(7.27.2)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
gives this story of the sudden stab of pain as a variant version, and Plutarch
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#75.3
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Alexander</I>, 75.3‑4)
	</A>
specifically denies it. Diodorus here explains the "cup of Heracles" mentioned by Plutarch. There was an annual festival of the death of Heracles on Mt. Oeta, with which Medius, as a Thessalian, was familiar. Its date has been unknown (M. P. Nilsson, <I>Geschichte der griechische Religion</I>, 1, 1941, p120), but this anecdote may indicate that it occurred in the Macedonian month of Caesius.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note83" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref83
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">83</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#5.4
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 10.5.4</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#15
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.15.12</A>. Curtius's narrative resumes at this point.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note84" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref84
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">84</A>
So also in Arrian, 7.26.3<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->. In
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#1.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 18.1.4</A>, Diodorus says "To the best," agreeing with the "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">optimus</SPAN>" of
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#5.5
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 10.5.5</A>, and the "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">dignissimus</SPAN>" of
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#5
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.5.8</A>.


<A ID="p467x"></A>It is true, of course, that <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">κράτιστος</SPAN> may mean "best" as well as "most powerful."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note85" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref85
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">85</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#5.5
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 10.5.5</A>;
Arrian, 7.26.3<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note86" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref86
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">86</A>
Alexander died on the 28th of Daesius (<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#76.4
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 76.4</A>, so also the Babylonian records<SPAN CLASS="emend">)</SPAN>,<A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('The Loeb edition —<BR>thru 40 years of reprintings! —<BR>fails to end the parenthesis; this is my guess.')"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> but Aristobulus
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#75.4
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 75.4)
	</A>
said the 30th; it was a hollow month, without any 29th, and Alexander died about sundown; this was the 10th of June), and it has been argued above that assassination of Philip and the accession of Alexander must have taken place in the same month
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/16D*.html#note114
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(p100, note 1)</A>. This would give Alexander thirteen years of reign, and this figure is actually given by the Oxyrhynchus Chronologer (<I>P. Oxy.</I> 1.12. v.31‑32). Since Daesius was the eighth Macedonian month, the "seven months" of Diodorus and the "eight months" of Arrian
(7.28.1)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->
represent exclusive and inclusive counting from the first new year after Alexander's accession. Cp. Beloch, <I>Griechische Geschichte</I><SPAN CLASS="superscript">2</SPAN>, 3.2.59.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note87" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref87
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">87</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#13
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.13.10</A>;
Arrian, 7.27.1<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->. See Addenda<!-- zzz -->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note88" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref88
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">88</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#14
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.14</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#77
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 77.1‑3</A>;
Arrian, 7.27<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->. The son's name was Iollas, but Justin associated with him his brothers Philip and Casander, the later king. Curtius does not mention this tradition.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note89" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref89
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">89</A>
Book 19.<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/19C*.html#49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49‑51</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/19C*.html#53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
53</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note90" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#ref90
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">90</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#5.19
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 10.5.19‑25</A>.



